node.text: This Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month, we’re sharing some #Perspectives from our athletes and employees. Team athletes Nina Williams (@sheneenagins) and Ashima Shiraishi (@ashimashiraishi) covering climbing, today’s political climate, and what it means to be AAPI in the outdoors. Hosted by Hannah Abuzaineh (@my_name_is_hj ), Senior Manager of Social Impact & The Explore Fund at The North Face.

node.title: AAPI Heritage Month with Nina and Ashima

node.text:
“Happy Pride Month! I didn’t come out until a month before I turned 26, yet I had been engaged for almost 4 months. I was scared that sponsors would not look at me or accept me for being gay. I worried that family and friends would turn their back to me. Coming out seemed like a way to kill a career before it even began.

Turns out, I was wrong. Friends, and (most) family have been nothing but supportive, and sponsors have stood by me through it all. I am thankful for the support so I can live life being my true self.

Yes, I will continue to paint my nails, wear 6-inch heels on Halloween, go to heavy metal shows, run in a speedo, and fight for the LGBTQ+ community. I don’t want others to have to wait almost 26 years to come out, that’s not okay.” Words by @coreewoltering
 
Join Coree Woltering and @bravetrails leader @alexisntransit tomorrow, Tuesday 22nd @ 12pm MT on an IG Live conversation to celebrate their experiences and find out more about Brave Trails.
